class Solution {
public:
    int MOD = 1e9 + 7;

    int zigZagArrays(int n, int l, int r) {
        int m = r - l + 1;

        vector<long long> up(m + 1), down(m + 1);

        // Length = 2
        for (int v = 1; v <= m; v++) {
            up[v] = v - 1;
            down[v] = m - v;
        }

        vector<long long> pref(m + 1, 0);
        vector<long long> suff(m + 2, 0);
        vector<long long> newUp(m + 1), newDown(m + 1);

        for (int len = 3; len <= n; len++) {
            for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
                pref[i] = (pref[i - 1] + down[i]) % MOD;
            }

            for (int i = m; i >= 1; i--) {
                suff[i] = (suff[i + 1] + up[i]) % MOD;
            }

            for (int x = 1; x <= m; x++) {
                newUp[x] = pref[x - 1];
                newDown[x] = suff[x + 1];
            }

            up = newUp;
            down = newDown;
        }

        long long ans = 0;
        for (int v = 1; v <= m; v++) {
            ans = (ans + up[v] + down[v]) % MOD;
        }

        return (int)ans;
    }
};

as we are given that no three consecutive elements should be strictly inreasing or strictly decreasing.
so 1 3 4 is not valid (strictly increasing) that means if we think as per direction, that is 3>1 => up and 4>3 => up so direction UU is not valid
similarly 4 3 1 is not vali(strictly decreasing), that means direction DD is also not valid.
so the direction of the resulting array should be either UDUD... or DUDU...
also one more thing, now we care about direction. so 101, 102 and 103 is same as 1,2,3 because both have same direction i.e. UU.
so now we do not care about actual values, so we shift the range [l,r] t [1,m] where m = r-l+1
suppose we have UDUD then next direction shoud be U so our future decisions depends on our past result, so this points to DP.
dp state:
up[v] = Number of valid arrays ending at value v whose last move was UP.
down[v] = Number of valid arrays ending at value v whose last move was DOWN.
base case: all valid arrays of length 2
up[v] = v-1 (all smaller elements than v)
down [v] = m-v (all greater elements than v)
dp transition:
if our prev move is UP then our current move should be down, that means to create a new down state in newDown[x] we must come from an UP state.
and our last value is x and direction is down, so prev value > x. Also we should come from up state. so newDown[x] = up[x+1] + up[x+2] + ... i.e. newDown[x] = sum of all up[v] where v>x
similarly for new up state we should come from a down state. so newUp[x] = down[1] + down[2] + down[3] + ... i.e. newUp[x] = sum of all down[v] where v<x
so in 6-2 and 6-3 we need sums from 1 to x and x+1 to m so we use prefix sum over down array and suffix sum over up array
so newDown[x] = suff[x+1] and newUp[x] = pref[x-1]
then up = newUp and down = newDown
at the end when we do this for length n, then we need to find the total valid arrays.
so an array can end with any value v and with either up direction or down direction. so we take sum of up[v] and down[v] for all v in [1,m]

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n*m) where m = r-l+1

Space complexity:
O(m)

